        detail: "<strong>Sacroiliac (SI) joint dysfunction</strong>—also called <strong>sacroiliac joint pain</strong> or <strong>SI joint pain</strong>—occurs when the joint connecting the base of the spine (sacrum) to the pelvis becomes inflamed (sacroiliitis) or moves abnormally (hypermobility or hypomobility). This condition can produce pain that often mimics <a href=\"/conditions/sciatica\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">sciatica</a> or <a href=\"/conditions/lumbar-herniated-disc\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">lumbar disc</a> issues, making an accurate diagnosis crucial. At Mountain Spine & Orthopedics, our specialists use provocative maneuvers and precision <a href=\"/treatments/sacroiliac-joint-injection\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">diagnostic SI joint injections</a> to confirm the SI joint as the pain source, ensuring therapy is correctly targeted for effective relief. Learn more about <a href=\"https://www.spine-health.com/conditions/lower-back-pain/sacroiliac-joint-dysfunction\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">sacroiliac joint dysfunction from Spine-Health</a>.",
