        treatment:
            "<h3>Non-Surgical Treatment Options</h3><p>Initial treatment typically focuses on conservative measures, including activity modification, <strong>physical therapy referrals</strong> to strengthen hip stabilizers and improve flexibility, and anti-inflammatory medications. Weight management can also significantly reduce stress on the hip joint.</p><h3>Injection or Interventional Care</h3><p>For patients with persistent pain, <strong>corticosteroid injections</strong> or <strong>biologic injections</strong> (such as PRP or hyaluronic acid) may provide relief by reducing inflammation and improving joint lubrication. These injections can be particularly effective for <a href=\"/conditions/hip-arthritis\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">hip arthritis</a> or <a href=\"/conditions/hip-bursitis\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">bursitis</a>.</p><h3>Surgical Treatment Options</h3><p>When conservative measures fail to provide adequate relief, surgical options may be considered. These range from minimally invasive procedures like <a href=\"/treatments/hip-arthroscopy-treatment\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">hip arthroscopy</a> for labral tears or impingement, to joint-preserving procedures, to <a href=\"/treatments/total-hip-replacement\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">total hip replacement</a> for advanced arthritis.</p>",
        pain_info:
            "<p>Hip pain can vary widely in character and location depending on the underlying cause. It may present as a <strong>dull ache</strong> deep in the groin, a <strong>sharp, stabbing pain</strong> with certain movements, or a <strong>burning sensation</strong> that radiates down the thigh.</p><p>The pain often worsens with weight-bearing activities, prolonged standing, or specific movements like getting in and out of a car. Our comprehensive approach addresses both the pain symptoms and the underlying cause, providing lasting relief and restoring function.</p>",
        prevent:
            "<p>While not all causes of hip pain can be prevented, several strategies can help reduce risk and maintain hip health:</p><ul><li>Maintaining a healthy weight to reduce stress on the hip joint</li><li>Regular low-impact exercise to strengthen hip stabilizers and maintain flexibility</li><li>Proper warm-up and stretching before physical activities</li><li>Using proper technique and equipment during sports or exercise</li><li>Addressing muscle imbalances and movement patterns through physical therapy</li><li>Seeking early evaluation from a <strong>hip specialist</strong> when symptoms first appear</li><li>Managing underlying conditions like arthritis or structural abnormalities proactively</li></ul>",
