        risk_fac: "<h2>What Causes Weightlifting Injuries?</h2><p>Weightlifting injuries occur due to a combination of biomechanical factors, training errors, and the heavy loads involved. Understanding these causes helps lifters implement effective prevention strategies.</p><p>According to <a href=\"https://orthoinfo.aaos.org/en/diseases--conditions/overuse-injuries-in-children/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">AAOS guidance on overuse injuries</a>, many weightlifting injuries result from repetitive stress without adequate recovery time.</p><h3>Technique and Form Factors</h3><ul><li>Improper lifting technique that places excessive stress on joints</li><li>Lifting too heavy before mastering proper form</li><li>Fatigue-induced form breakdown during high-rep sets</li><li>Rounded back during deadlifts or squats</li><li>Compensating for previous injuries or limitations</li></ul><h3>Training and Load Management Errors</h3><ul><li>Lifting too heavy too soon (rapid progression)</li><li>Inadequate warm-up before lifting</li><li>Insufficient recovery time between training sessions</li><li>Sudden increases in training volume or intensity</li><li>Pushing through pain or ignoring warning signs</li></ul><h3>Physical Conditioning Factors</h3><ul><li>Muscle imbalances (weak core, tight hip flexors, weak posterior chain)</li><li>Limited mobility or flexibility</li><li>Inadequate strength base for heavy loads</li><li>Previous injuries that weren't fully rehabilitated</li></ul><h3>Programming Factors</h3><ul><li>Unbalanced programming (overemphasizing certain movements)</li><li>Lack of periodization or deload weeks</li><li>Training to failure too frequently</li></ul>",
