        body: "Golfer's elbow (medial epicondylitis) is an overuse injury causing pain on the inside of the elbow from repetitive wrist flexion and gripping activities.",
        detail: "<p><strong>Golfer's elbow</strong> (<strong>medial epicondylitis</strong>) is a painful condition affecting the tendons that attach to the bony prominence on the inside of the elbow. Despite its name, this condition is not limited to golfers—it commonly affects anyone who performs repetitive wrist flexion, gripping, or throwing motions. It is closely related to <a href=\"/conditions/tennis-elbow\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">tennis elbow</a>, which affects the outside of the elbow.</p><p>The condition develops when repetitive stress causes <strong>micro-tears and degeneration</strong> in the flexor-pronator tendon group. At Mountain Spine & Orthopedics, our specialists use targeted evaluation and advanced treatment options including <a href=\"/treatments/stem-cell-treatment\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">platelet-rich plasma (PRP) injections</a> to promote tendon healing and restore function.</p>",
        what_sym: "<p>Common symptoms of golfer's elbow include:</p><ul><li><strong>Pain and tenderness</strong> on the inner side of the elbow that may radiate down the forearm</li><li>Pain that worsens with <strong>wrist flexion</strong>, gripping, or shaking hands</li><li><strong>Stiffness</strong> in the elbow, especially in the morning</li><li>Weakness in the hands and wrists</li><li><strong>Numbness or tingling</strong> radiating into the ring and small fingers (if the ulnar nerve is involved)</li></ul>",
        risk_fac: "<p>Risk factors for developing golfer's elbow include:</p><ul><li>Repetitive wrist and forearm motions from sports (golf, tennis, throwing sports) or occupations</li><li>Using improper technique or equipment during sports activities</li><li>Jobs involving repetitive arm movements—plumbing, carpentry, construction</li><li>Age between 40 and 60 years</li><li>Obesity and smoking, which impair tissue healing</li></ul>",
        diagnose: "<p>Diagnosis is primarily clinical, based on the location of pain and provocative testing. Our specialists perform the <strong>resisted wrist flexion test</strong> and assess for tenderness over the medial epicondyle. We differentiate golfer's elbow from ulnar nerve problems and other conditions.</p><p>High-resolution <strong>ultrasound</strong> provides dynamic evaluation of tendon integrity, while MRI may be used for complex cases or when surgery is being considered. We offer complimentary imaging reviews to assess your condition thoroughly.</p>",
        treatment: "<h3>Non-Surgical Treatment</h3><p>Most patients with golfer's elbow improve with conservative care:</p><ul><li><strong>Rest and activity modification</strong> to avoid aggravating movements</li><li>Ice application and anti-inflammatory medications</li><li>Counterforce bracing to reduce tendon strain</li><li>Physical therapy with <strong>eccentric strengthening exercises</strong></li><li><strong>PRP injections</strong> or corticosteroid injections for persistent symptoms</li></ul><h3>Surgical Options</h3><p>When conservative treatment fails after 6-12 months, <a href=\"/treatments/golfers-elbow-surgery\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">golfer's elbow surgery</a> may be recommended. The procedure involves releasing the damaged tendon tissue and promoting healthy tendon regeneration. Our surgeons use minimally invasive techniques for optimal outcomes.</p>",
