        body: "Heel pain has many causes including plantar fasciitis, heel spurs, and Achilles tendonitis. Accurate diagnosis ensures effective treatment.",
        detail: "<p><strong>Heel pain</strong> is one of the most common foot complaints, affecting millions of people and often significantly impacting daily activities. While <a href=\"/conditions/plantar-fasciitis\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">plantar fasciitis</a> is the most frequent cause, heel pain can result from numerous conditions affecting different structures of the heel.</p><p>The heel bears significant force with every step—up to 1.5 times your body weight when walking and 3 times when running. This makes it vulnerable to overuse injuries, stress fractures, and degenerative changes. At Mountain Spine & Orthopedics, our <strong>foot and ankle specialists</strong> carefully evaluate heel pain to determine the precise cause and create targeted treatment plans.</p><p>Understanding whether your heel pain originates from the plantar fascia, Achilles tendon, heel bone, or surrounding nerves is crucial for effective treatment. Our comprehensive evaluation identifies the source of your pain and addresses contributing factors like biomechanical issues and footwear problems.</p>",
        what_sym: "<p>Heel pain symptoms vary depending on the underlying cause. Carefully noting your symptom pattern helps our specialists make an accurate diagnosis.</p><h3>Common Symptom Patterns</h3><ul><li><strong>Bottom of heel pain (worse in morning):</strong> Suggests <a href=\"/conditions/plantar-fasciitis\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">plantar fasciitis</a></li><li><strong>Back of heel pain:</strong> May indicate <a href=\"/conditions/achilles-tendonitis\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">Achilles tendonitis</a>, Haglund's deformity, or retrocalcaneal bursitis</li><li><strong>Pain with activity that worsens over time:</strong> Could suggest a stress fracture</li><li><strong>Burning, tingling, or numbness:</strong> May indicate nerve entrapment (Baxter's nerve or tarsal tunnel syndrome)</li><li><strong>Heel pain in children 8-14:</strong> Often Sever's disease (calcaneal apophysitis)</li></ul><h3>Warning Signs Requiring Urgent Evaluation</h3><ul><li>Severe pain after an injury</li><li>Inability to bear weight</li><li>Swelling, redness, or warmth suggesting infection</li><li>Heel pain with fever</li><li>Numbness or tingling in the foot</li></ul>",
        risk_fac: "<p>Multiple factors contribute to heel pain development:</p><ul><li><strong>Overuse and overtraining:</strong> Sudden increases in activity intensity or duration</li><li><strong>Improper footwear:</strong> Shoes with inadequate support or worn-out cushioning</li><li><strong>Biomechanical issues:</strong> <a href=\"/conditions/flat-feet\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">Flat feet</a>, high arches, or overpronation</li><li><strong>Obesity:</strong> Increased heel loading with excess body weight</li><li><strong>Occupational factors:</strong> Jobs requiring prolonged standing on hard surfaces</li><li><strong>Tight calf muscles:</strong> Increase tension on the Achilles and plantar fascia</li><li><strong>Age:</strong> Heel fat pad atrophy and reduced tissue elasticity with aging</li><li><strong>High-impact sports:</strong> Running, basketball, and jumping sports</li></ul>",
        diagnose: "<p>Accurate diagnosis of heel pain requires identifying the specific structure involved. Our evaluation includes:</p><ul><li><strong>Detailed history:</strong> When pain occurs, what makes it better or worse, activity changes</li><li><strong>Physical examination:</strong> Palpation, range of motion, neurological testing, gait analysis</li><li><strong>X-rays:</strong> Identify bone spurs, fractures, and structural abnormalities</li><li><strong>Ultrasound:</strong> Real-time evaluation of plantar fascia and Achilles tendon thickness</li><li><strong>MRI:</strong> Detailed soft tissue evaluation; we offer complimentary <a href=\"/find-care/free-mri-review\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">MRI reviews</a></li></ul><h3>Conditions We Diagnose and Treat</h3><ul><li>Plantar fasciitis and plantar fascial tears</li><li>Heel spurs (calcaneal spurs)</li><li>Achilles tendonitis and tendinopathy</li><li>Haglund's deformity (\"pump bump\")</li><li>Retrocalcaneal bursitis</li><li>Calcaneal stress fractures</li><li>Fat pad atrophy</li><li>Tarsal tunnel syndrome and nerve entrapment</li><li>Sever's disease (in children)</li></ul>",
        treatment: "<p>Treatment for heel pain targets the specific underlying cause.</p><h3>Conservative Treatment (Effective for Most Patients)</h3><ul><li><strong>Rest and activity modification:</strong> Reducing aggravating activities</li><li><strong>Ice therapy:</strong> 15-20 minutes several times daily</li><li><strong>Stretching:</strong> Calf and plantar fascia stretching exercises</li><li><strong>Proper footwear:</strong> Supportive shoes with adequate cushioning</li><li><strong>Orthotics:</strong> Custom or over-the-counter arch supports and heel cups</li><li><strong>Night splints:</strong> Maintain stretch while sleeping</li><li><strong>Physical therapy:</strong> Targeted strengthening and flexibility programs</li><li><strong>Anti-inflammatory medications:</strong> NSAIDs for pain and swelling</li></ul><h3>Interventional Options</h3><ul><li><strong>Corticosteroid injections:</strong> <a href=\"/treatments/anti-inflammatory-injections-for-joint-and-spine-pain\" class=\"text-blue-600 hover:underline\">Ultrasound-guided injections</a> for targeted relief</li><li><strong>PRP injections:</strong> Platelet-rich plasma to promote healing</li><li><strong>Extracorporeal shockwave therapy (ESWT):</strong> Stimulates tissue healing</li></ul><h3>Surgical Options (When Conservative Care Fails)</h3><ul><li>Plantar fascia release</li><li>Bone spur removal</li><li>Achilles tendon debridement or repair</li><li>Nerve decompression</li></ul>",
        pain_info: "<p>Heel pain can originate from multiple sources, each with distinct pain characteristics. <strong>Plantar fasciitis</strong> causes sharp pain at the bottom of the heel, classically worse with the first steps in the morning. <strong>Achilles tendonitis</strong> produces pain at the back of the heel that worsens with activity. <strong>Stress fractures</strong> cause progressive pain with weight-bearing. <strong>Nerve entrapment</strong> produces burning or tingling pain. Understanding your pain pattern helps identify the cause.</p>",
        prevent: "<p>Keeping your heels healthy requires attention to footwear, stretching, and training habits.</p><ul><li><strong>Wear supportive footwear:</strong> Replace worn shoes regularly</li><li><strong>Stretch daily:</strong> Calf and Achilles stretching reduces heel stress</li><li><strong>Progress activities gradually:</strong> Avoid sudden increases in training</li><li><strong>Maintain healthy weight:</strong> Reduces heel loading</li><li><strong>Use cushioned insoles:</strong> Especially on hard surfaces</li><li><strong>Vary your activities:</strong> Cross-training reduces repetitive stress</li><li><strong>Address biomechanical issues:</strong> Custom orthotics for flat feet or high arches</li><li><strong>Strengthen foot muscles:</strong> Towel curls and marble pickups build intrinsic foot strength</li></ul>",
        why_choose_us: "<p>Mountain Spine & Orthopedics provides <strong>comprehensive heel pain evaluation and treatment</strong>. Our foot and ankle specialists use advanced diagnostic techniques to identify the precise cause of your pain, then create targeted treatment plans. We offer the full spectrum of care from conservative management to advanced procedures, ensuring you receive the most appropriate treatment for your condition.</p>",
